title: Kylie Jenner returns to her app writing about fishnets
text:
She vowed to never write again for her own site but this star's love of fishnets was so great she could not help but backtrack.
Kylie Jenner returned to her app on Tuesday, less than a month after she said she would no longer post personally on the phone app and subscription website.
TheKylieJenner.com shared a post written in the first person about the fishnet style trend the star is currently enjoying - and suggests she started.
Change of heart: Kylie Jenner (pictured in Costa Rica over the weekend) returned to her app on Tuesday, less than a month after she said she would no longer post personally on the phone app and subscription website

Posting a collage of her favourite shots of herself and models wearing the net stockings, the star made no mention of why she had decided to lift her own self-imposed ban.
The post said: 'I've been really into fishnets for a while and suddenly the look is everywhere. Coincidence? LOL.
'I like wearing them under ripped jeans or an oversize tee. I'm also into the idea of fishnet bodysuits and dresses.'
The star the shared some e-retail links so fans can recreate her look.
Just really loves fishnets: The star spoke of how she may be behind the style trend, 'I've been really into fishnets for a while and suddenly the look is everywhere. Coincidence? LOL'
At the start of this month an enraged Kylie publicly declared she would not post personally on the $2.99 month app, leaving posts to her pals and her team at developers Whalerock.
The move followed a post - purporting to have been written by Kylie herself - that listed 'things I do to spoil my man!'
It included 'Make your sex life fun! Spice things up with lingerie, toys and massages'.
'Lingerie, toys and massages!' At the start of this month an enraged Kylie publicly declared she would not post personally on the $2.99 month app, leaving posts to her pals and her team at developers Whalerock, after a saucy post went up without her approval
The 19-year-old quickly took to Twitter to deny she had anything to do with it.
'Hey guys from now on I won't be posting personally on my app anymore...' she wrote. 'A post went up today quoting something that I NEVER EVER said or saw. A very personal post that I would never ever approve. And it's unfair to me and you to think that those were my words.I'm sorry and I know we will figure something out so we can all be satisfied,' she added, before signing off: 'Love You'.
She had also tweeted 'It will strictly be just from my team and my friends keeping you guys updated' — but then deleted it.
Unapproved: The post on her app and website detailed how Kylie got up early to make Tyga breakfast in bed, baked cookies 'for no reason', cooked for all of Tyga's friends whenever they came to the house and used sex toys to spice things up in the bedroom
I didn't do it: The 19-year-old quickly took to Twitter to deny she had anything to do with it
Whalerock - who developed the apps and has a team helping Kylie with the content - later posted an apology for the 'mistake', claiming post was a draft erroneously set live without her blessing.
'To Kylie's fans: This morning, a drafted article was inadvertently posted for a short period of time on Kylie's app. This was a draft that was not in Kylie's words, was not Kylie's idea and had not been sent to her for approval,' they wrote.
'We'd like to sincerely apologize to Kylie for this mistake and the fans because it was never our intention to misrepresent Kylie and Kylie's voice. We deeply regret that this happened and will work hard to ensure this never occurs again.'
Paying for what? Indeed many of her followers on social media questioned why they were paying for content that didn't come from her
